et/images/095158fig10b.jpeg" height="1147" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig11.jpeg" height="1338" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Aortic root dilatation after an arterial switch procedure for treatment of <span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-transposition of the great arteries in an 18-year-old man. Three-chamber view of the heart from SSFP MR imaging shows a dilated aortic root <i>(A)</i> with a low-signal-intensity jet indicative of regurgitation. The aortic root has a diameter of 6.5 cm. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig12a.jpeg" height="1527" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig12b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1742" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig12c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1714" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig12d.jpeg" height="1147" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig13a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1798" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig13b.jpeg" height="1396" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig13c.jpeg" height="1368" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig14a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1420" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig14b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1787" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig15.jpeg" height="1622" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Preoperative appearance of DORV in a female infant. Axial black-blood spin-echo MR image obtained at the level of the outflow tracts shows the conal musculature <i>(CM)</i> surrounding the origins of both great arteries. The aorta <i>(A)</i> and pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i> are side by side, with the aorta on the right (<span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-malposition).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig16a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1052" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig16b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1014" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig16c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1037" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig16d.jpeg" height="1280" width="1033" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig17.jpeg" height="1600" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> DORV with total anomalous pulmonary venous return in a newborn female infant. Volume-rendered image from gadolinium-enhanced 3D MR angiography shows pulmonary venous confluence posterior to the left atrium (arrowheads) with drainage via a vertical vein (arrows) into the severely dilated left superior vena cava <i>(LSVC)</i> and the left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig18a.jpeg" height="1488" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig18b.jpeg" height="1478" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig19.jpeg" height="703" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Diagrams show two commonly used systems for classifying truncus arteriosus. <i>Top row:</i> In the Collett and Edwards system, type I truncus arteriosus is characterized by the origin of both pulmonary arteries from a short pulmonary trunk; type II is characterized by the separate origin of the pulmonary arteries from the posterior aspect of the truncus; type III is characterized by the separate origin of the pulmonary arteries from the lateral aspect of the truncus; and type IV is characterized by a pseudotruncus—currently considered a form of pulmonary atresia—with a ventricular septal defect. <i>Bottom row:</i> In the Van Praagh system, types A1 and A2 truncus arteriosus are equivalent to Collett and Edwards types I and II, respectively; type A3 represents atresia of the left or right pulmonary artery, with collateral flow to the ipsilateral lung; and type A4 is characterized by the presence of an associated interrupted aortic arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig20.jpeg" height="1280" width="831" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Collett and Edwards type I truncus arteriosus in a male newborn. Volume-rendered image from preoperative gadolinium-enhanced 3D MR angiography shows a short pulmonary trunk <i>(PT)</i> that arises from the posterior aspect of the truncus arteriosus <i>(TA)</i> and gives rise to both pulmonary arteries, which are of good size. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery, <i>RPA</i> = right pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig21.jpeg" height="1508" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Volume-rendered image from postoperative gadolinium-enhanced 3D MR angiography shows a repaired truncus arteriosus with a stenosis (arrow) in the distal part of the right ventricle–pulmonary artery conduit.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig22.jpeg" height="516" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Diagrams show the three types of interrupted aortic arch, which are differentiated by their location. Type A interruption (left) occurs distal to the left subclavian artery origin; type B interruption, the most common type (middle), occurs between the origins of the left common carotid artery and left subclavian artery; and type C interruption (right) occurs between the origins of the innominate and left common carotid arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig23a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1261" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig23b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1798" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.304095158/asset/images/095158fig24.jpeg" height="1800" width="1335" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Postoperative appearance of interrupted aortic arch with proximal anastomotic narrowing in a 30-year-old man. Oblique sagittal 2D balanced SSFP MR image depicts narrowing of the anastomosis in the proximal part of the aortic arch (arrow) and absence of dilatation in the proximal ascending aorta <i>(A)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.304095158&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Restivo A, Piacentini G, Placidi S, Saffirio C, Marino B. Cardiac outflow tract: a review of s